        Over the next hour, Holloway explains how the journey would work — and it is, predictably, complicated.

        Multiple fruiting bodies consult coordination documents that materialize as fungal growth along the walls as Holloway outlines the plan.

        Holloway says, "The route to Elder Heartwood's grove passes through seven distinct network territories — each territory has its own coordination network, protocols, and jurisdiction requirements. Territory One is here — this facility's network. Territory Two begins approximately three days' travel east. Then Territory Three, Four — culminating in Territory Seven, where Elder Heartwood's Ancient Grove resides."

        I take notes on a salvaged data pad. Scout watches from my lap, occasionally bouncing encouragingly.

        I ask, "Three days between territories? So, roughly twenty-one days total?"

        Holloway replies, "Approximately! Though some territories are smaller, others larger — and travel pace depends on various factors — terrain conditions, rest requirements, processing time at territorial boundaries..."

        I ask, "Processing time?"

        Holloway says, "Each territorial boundary requires coordination transfer — permissions verification — documentation review — guide handoff protocols."

        Of course — bureaucracy doesn't stop just because you're traveling.

        ¶

        But still — two to three weeks of moving forward, making progress, getting closer to the goal, versus two months of sitting still.

        I ask, "What about guides? You mentioned guide assignments?"

        Holloway says, "Yes! Travelers require guides familiar with routes and territorial protocols. Different networks specialize in different terrains — some guides excel at forest navigation, others at river crossing, others at mountain passages. You'd be assigned appropriate guides for each territory."

        I ask, "Multiple guides? Like, different plants for different sections?"

        Holloway answers, "Exactly. Each territory would provide guides skilled in their local conditions. They'd escort you to the next boundary, coordinate transfer, and return home while the next territory's guides take over."

        I try to imagine it — a plant relay race, with me as the baton being passed between runners. Weird, but functional.

        Holloway says, "Oh yes. Formal arrival notification would be filed through coordination channels — Elder's grove would prepare appropriate reception protocols. Though..." — Holloway's voice takes on that uncertain quality again — "this is quite unusual. Most beings simply wait for query responses. Physical journeys to Elder Heartwood are rare."

        Holloway adds, "But possible. Yes — absolutely possible. Just uncommon."

        Buddy says, "Kira, I should mention that extended travel involves certain risks — unfamiliar terrain, potential exposure to elements, physical exertion while still recovering from injury —"

        I say, "My injury's healed — Remedy cleared me yesterday. Wound fully closed, tissue regenerated. I'm fine."
      </text>
