        Holloway says, "Physically, yes! But metabolically, you're still adjusting to the local nutrition. Extended travel might stress your system further."

        Valid point—annoying, but valid.

        I ask Holloway, "What about food? For the journey? I can't exactly pack mushroom paste for three weeks."

        Holloway replies, "Each territory would provide appropriate nutrition—guide plants can synthesize compounds compatible with human requirements. We'd transmit your dietary documentation ahead via network coordination. Meals would be available at each stop."

        Scout bounces approvingly—mushroom paste will follow me on the road.

        Fantastic.

        I ask, "Shelter? Water? All the basic survival stuff?"

        Holloway says, "Territories maintain rest facilities for travelers—smaller than this facility, but functional. Water access varies by terrain; some territories have abundant springs, others require more careful resource management. Your guides would ensure appropriate provisions."

        I process this—so basically, a bureaucratic road trip: multiple territories, multiple guides, documentation at every boundary, mushroom paste the whole way.

        ¶

        And at the end, Elder Heartwood—an actual face-to-face meeting instead of waiting months for relay communication.

        I ask, "How soon could I leave if I filed the travel request?"

        Holloway consults, then says, "Guide availability varies... Current assessment suggests… perhaps three to four days for arrangements—filing the request, securing guide assignments, preparing documentation, coordinating with receiving territories..."

        Three to four days—so, total timeline: call it four days of prep plus twenty-one days of travel—twenty-five days, roughly.

        Versus the fifty-one to seventy-seven days of waiting I was counting this morning—half the time, maybe less.

        And I'd be _doing something_.

        Scout bounces in my lap, sensing the energy building.

        Holloway says gently, "There are considerations to discuss—the journey involves challenges: traveling through unfamiliar territories, adapting to different network protocols, physical exertion over multiple weeks. And Elder Heartwood exists in very slow time—you could journey three weeks and still wait additional time for Elder to process your presence and formulate guidance."

        I say, "But I'd be there—in person. Able to communicate directly once Elder was ready. Not waiting for relay transmission through seven territories."

        Holloway replies, "True! Direct presence does facilitate certain types of communication. Though I should mention—Elder Heartwood's wisdom is profound, but Elder may not have the answers you seek. They handle exceptions, yes, but 'stranded human needing rescue' may be beyond even Elder's capabilities."

        I've considered that, of course—Elder Heartwood is very old and very wise, not a magic solution to impossible problems.

        But sitting here waiting isn't a solution either.
      </text>
