        I say carefully, "I understand. Elder might not be able to help, but they're still my best option—and I'd rather spend three weeks trying to reach them than three months waiting to find out they can't help anyway."

        Holloway's fruiting bodies rustle—consideration, maybe approval.

        Holloway says, "Your reasoning is sound. Active pursuit versus passive waiting—both have merit, but for your particular situation, I think the journey might serve you well. Even if Elder's guidance proves limited, the experience of traveling through network territories, meeting different plant communities, engaging with diverse perspectives—that has value too."

        It does— I haven't thought about it that way, but Holloway's right. I'll learn more in three weeks of travel than three months in this facility—and I'll go completely insane if I have to eat mushroom paste in the same quarters for two more months.

        I say, "I want to do it—I'm ready to file the travel request and make the journey."

        Scout bounces—big, enthusiastic. Buddy makes a thoughtful sound.

        The AI says, "Kira, I'm obligated to note that this involves significant uncertainty and potential risk—"

        I say, "Yeah, I know. I crashed on an alien planet last week. My baseline risk tolerance is pretty high right now."

        The AI says, "Fair point. I'll support whatever decision you make. Though I should mention: I'd be traveling with you, yes? I have limited battery reserves, but I can monitor your health and provide companionship throughout the journey."

        I say, "Of course you're coming—*both of you*."

        I look down at Scout and ask, "You want to go on a road trip through bureaucratic plant territories?"

        Scout bounces three times—big and enthusiastic.

        Holloway says warmly, "Excellent! Then let's begin the travel request documentation. This will require several forms, naturally—Traveler Information—Route Selection—Guide Request Specifications—Territorial Coordination Notifications—Resource Requirement Assessments…"

        More forms—obviously. But these forms have purpose—these forms lead somewhere.

        I open a fresh document on the data pad and say, "I'm ready. Let's do this."

        ¶

        Because waiting is over.

        The journey is beginning.
      </text>
